              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=24708555#p24708555" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">shoe</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I guess it's not possible though - on some level every message has to have a to address.  It doesn't really matter if it's user@domain or a 50 digit random string, you can always translate it back to the source.</div><br /><a href="http://tormail.org" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Tor Mail</a> (or similar other services, or set up your own). If you want to use email in an obfuscated fashion, well now you really are talking about something that's a lot more work. All the standard warnings that come with using Tor apply just as strongly, or even more so depending on exactly how important your anonymity is since you're sending actual content. It's not impossible though to at least make sure you aren't low hanging fruit.<br /><br />Or I guess in many countries you could also just create throwaway accounts on free services at will and send them via war driving, though that requires significant work as well.

              

              
              
